A `const otSrpService *` would not protect against access to the pointed char buffer.

In ` const` structure, the member variables would be treated as `const`, so no one can change or assign new values to them. The `mFullName` would be treated as `char * const mFullName` (which means the `mFullName` pointer value itself cannot change but the buffer to which it points can be changed) and not `const char *const mFullName`.

Here is small test for this:
```
    struct Test
    {
        char *mName;
    };

    char name[2];
    char name2[2];
    Test test;
    const Test *tp = &test;

    test.mName = name;
    name[0] = 'A';
    name[1] = 0;

    printf("name:\"%s\"\n", tp->mName);

    tp->mName[0] = 'B';    // This works even though `tp` is `const Test *`
    printf("name:\"%s\"\n", tp->mName);

    // tp->mName = name2; // This errors "cannot assign to variable 'tp' with const-qualified type 'const Test *'"
```

