Thanks @morningboata.  

Is the goal of the PR to add mechanism to enable/disable certain features/behaviors at run-time (for some subset of features)?

If so, I suggest it may be simpler and more straight-forward  to add public APIs to control this:
- Some existing features already provide this, e.g. `BORDER_ROUTING` we have `otBorderRoutingSetEnabled()` to enable the functionality at run-time, similarly for SRP server, and client, ... 
- The example you mention is `NAT64_TRANSLATOR`. 
  -  We can add new API `otNat64TranslationSetEnabled()` for this instead of using `IS_FEATURE_ENABLED()` model.
   - We can still use `if()` checks to see if the behavior is enabled (at run-time) before calling its methods. For example:
```c++
Error Ip6::ProcessReceiveCallback(...) 
{
    // ...

#if OPENTHREAD_CONFIG_NAT64_TRANSLATOR_ENABLE
    if (Get<Nat64::Translator>().IsEnabled())
    { 
        // Use Translator methods only when enabled.
    }
    else
#endif
    {
        // When feature is not enabled (at compile or run-time).
        // ...
    }
}
```

which I think is simpler to read and follow compared to:
```c++
Error Ip6::ProcessReceiveCallback(...) {
...
#if IS_FEATURE_ENABLED_IN_COMPILE(NAT64_TRANSLATOR)
   // Use IS_FEATURE_ENABLED to guard new feature logic.
   if (IS_FEATURE_ENABLED(NAT64_TRANSLATOR)) {
   // Add new feature logic.
   }
#endif
...
}
```

- Another advantage I see is that with enable/disable API, the API will be next to other related APIs of the feature (same file/module) vs. having it be determined in a platform `otPlatIsFeatureEnabled()` API call (shared for all).

